<img src=3D"https://d26tpo4cm8sb6k.cloudfront.net/img/fraction/fraction-pie=
.png" width=3D"165" height=3D"168" alt=3D"3 over 8" align=3D"right">
<p>In mathematics, a fraction is a number that represents a part of a whole=
. It consists of a numerator and a denominator. The numerator represents th=
e number of equal parts of a whole, while the denominator is the total numb=
er of parts that make up said whole. For example, in the fraction of <span =
class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">3</span><span class=3D"fracden">8</s=
pan></span>, the numerator is 3, and the denominator is 8. A more illustrat=
ive example could involve a pie with 8 slices. 1 of those 8 slices would co=
nstitute the numerator of a fraction, while the total of 8 slices that comp=
rises the whole pie would be the denominator. If a person were to eat 3 sli=
ces, the remaining fraction of the pie would therefore be <span class=3D"fr=
ac"><span class=3D"fracnum">5</span><span class=3D"fracden">8</span></span>=
 as shown in the image to the right. Note that the denominator of a fractio=
n cannot be 0, as it would make the fraction undefined. Fractions can under=
go many different operations, some of which are mentioned below.</p>


<h3>Addition:</h3>
<p>Unlike adding and subtracting integers such as 2 and 8, fractions requir=
e a common denominator to undergo these operations. One method for finding =
a common denominator involves multiplying the numerators and denominators o=
f all of the fractions involved by the product of the denominators of each =
fraction. Multiplying all of the denominators ensures that the new denomina=
tor is certain to be a multiple of each individual denominator. The numerat=
ors also need to be multiplied by the appropriate factors to preserve the v=
alue of the fraction as a whole. This is arguably the simplest way to ensur=
e that the fractions have a common denominator. However, in most cases, the=
 solutions to these equations will not appear in simplified form (the provi=
ded calculator computes the simplification automatically). Below is an exam=
ple using this method.</p>

<div style=3D"text-align: center;">
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">a</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">b</span></span> +
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">c</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">d</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">a=C3=97d</span><span class=3D=
"fracden">b=C3=97d</span></span> +
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">c=C3=97b</span><span class=3D=
"fracden">d=C3=97b</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">ad + bc</span><span class=3D"=
fracden">bd</span></span>
</div>
<div style=3D"text-align: center;">EX:
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">3</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">4</span></span> +
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">1</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">6</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">3=C3=976</span><span class=3D=
"fracden">4=C3=976</span></span> +
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">1=C3=974</span><span class=3D=
"fracden">6=C3=974</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">22</span><span class=3D"fracd=
en">24</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">11</span><span class=3D"fracd=
en">12</span></span>
</div>

<p>This process can be used for any number of fractions. Just multiply the =
numerators and denominators of each fraction in the problem by the product =
of the denominators of all the other fractions (not including its own respe=
ctive denominator) in the problem.</p>

<div style=3D"text-align: center;">EX:
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">1</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">4</span></span> +
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">1</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">6</span></span> +
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">1</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">2</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">1=C3=976=C3=972</span><span c=
lass=3D"fracden">4=C3=976=C3=972</span></span> +
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">1=C3=974=C3=972</span><span c=
lass=3D"fracden">6=C3=974=C3=972</span></span> +
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">1=C3=974=C3=976</span><span c=
lass=3D"fracden">2=C3=974=C3=976</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">12</span><span class=3D"fracd=
en">48</span></span> +
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">8</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">48</span></span> +
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">24</span><span class=3D"fracd=
en">48</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">44</span><span class=3D"fracd=
en">48</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">11</span><span class=3D"fracd=
en">12</span></span>
</div>

<p>An alternative method for finding a common denominator is to determine t=
he <a href=3D"https://www.calculator.net/lcm-calculator.html">least common =
multiple (LCM)</a> for the denominators, then add or subtract the numerator=
s as one would an integer. Using the least common multiple can be more effi=
cient and is more likely to result in a fraction in simplified form. In the=
 example above, the denominators were 4, 6, and 2. The least common multipl=
e is the first shared multiple of these three numbers.</p>
<table align=3D"center">
	<tbody><tr><td>Multiples of 2: 2, 4, 6, 8 10, <b>12</b></td></tr>
	<tr><td>Multiples of 4: 4, 8, <b>12</b></td></tr>
	<tr><td>Multiples of 6: 6, <b>12</b></td></tr>
</tbody></table>
<p>The first multiple they all share is 12, so this is the least common mul=
tiple. To complete an addition (or subtraction) problem, multiply the numer=
ators and denominators of each fraction in the problem by whatever value wi=
ll make the denominators 12, then add the numerators.</p>
<div style=3D"text-align: center;">EX:
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">1</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">4</span></span> +
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">1</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">6</span></span> +
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">1</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">2</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">1=C3=973</span><span class=3D=
"fracden">4=C3=973</span></span> +
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">1=C3=972</span><span class=3D=
"fracden">6=C3=972</span></span> +
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">1=C3=976</span><span class=3D=
"fracden">2=C3=976</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">3</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">12</span></span> +
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">2</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">12</span></span> +
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">6</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">12</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">11</span><span class=3D"fracd=
en">12</span></span>
</div>

<h3>Subtraction:</h3>
<p>Fraction subtraction is essentially the same as fraction addition. A com=
mon denominator is required for the operation to occur. Refer to the additi=
on section as well as the equations below for clarification.</p>
<div style=3D"text-align: center;">
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">a</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">b</span></span> =E2=80=93
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">c</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">d</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">a=C3=97d</span><span class=3D=
"fracden">b=C3=97d</span></span> =E2=80=93
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">c=C3=97b</span><span class=3D=
"fracden">d=C3=97b</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">ad =E2=80=93 bc</span><span c=
lass=3D"fracden">bd</span></span>
</div>
<div style=3D"text-align: center;">EX:
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">3</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">4</span></span> =E2=80=93
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">1</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">6</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">3=C3=976</span><span class=3D=
"fracden">4=C3=976</span></span> =E2=80=93
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">1=C3=974</span><span class=3D=
"fracden">6=C3=974</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">14</span><span class=3D"fracd=
en">24</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">7</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">12</span></span>
</div>

<h3>Multiplication:</h3>
<p>Multiplying fractions is fairly straightforward. Unlike adding and subtr=
acting, it is not necessary to compute a common denominator in order to mul=
tiply fractions. Simply, the numerators and denominators of each fraction a=
re multiplied, and the result forms a new numerator and denominator. If pos=
sible, the solution should be simplified. Refer to the equations below for =
clarification. </p>
<div style=3D"text-align: center;">
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">a</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">b</span></span> =C3=97
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">c</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">d</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">ac</span><span class=3D"fracd=
en">bd</span></span>
</div>
<div style=3D"text-align: center;">EX:
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">3</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">4</span></span> =C3=97
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">1</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">6</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">3</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">24</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">1</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">8</span></span>
</div>

<h3>Division:</h3>
<p>The process for dividing fractions is similar to that for multiplying fr=
actions. In order to divide fractions, the fraction in the numerator is mul=
tiplied by the reciprocal of the fraction in the denominator. The reciproca=
l of a number <b>a</b> is simply <span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnu=
m">1</span><span class=3D"fracden">a</span></span>. When a is a fraction, t=
his essentially involves exchanging the position of the numerator and the d=
enominator. The reciprocal of the fraction <span class=3D"frac"><span class=
=3D"fracnum">3</span><span class=3D"fracden">4</span></span> would therefor=
e be <span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">4</span><span class=3D"fr=
acden">3</span></span>. Refer to the equations below for clarification. </p=
>
<div style=3D"text-align: center;">
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">a</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">b</span></span> /
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">c</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">d</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">a</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">b</span></span> =C3=97
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">d</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">c</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">ad</span><span class=3D"fracd=
en">bc</span></span>
</div>
<div style=3D"text-align: center;">EX:
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">3</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">4</span></span> /
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">1</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">6</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">3</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">4</span></span> =C3=97
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">6</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">1</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">18</span><span class=3D"fracd=
en">4</span></span> =3D
	<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">9</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">2</span></span>
</div>

<h3>Simplification:</h3>
<p>It is often easier to work with simplified fractions. As such, fraction =
solutions are commonly expressed in their simplified forms. <span class=3D"=
frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">220</span><span class=3D"fracden">440</span><=
/span> for example, is more cumbersome than <span class=3D"frac"><span clas=
s=3D"fracnum">1</span><span class=3D"fracden">2</span></span>. The calculat=
or provided returns fraction inputs in both improper fraction form as well =
as mixed number form. In both cases, fractions are presented in their lowes=
t forms by dividing both numerator and denominator by their greatest common=
 factor.</p>

<h3>Converting between fractions and decimals:</h3>
<p>Converting from decimals to fractions is straightforward. It does, howev=
er, require the understanding that each decimal place to the right of the d=
ecimal point represents a power of 10; the first decimal place being 10<sup=
>1</sup>, the second 10<sup>2</sup>, the third 10<sup>3</sup>, and so on. S=
imply determine what power of 10 the decimal extends to, use that power of =
10 as the denominator, enter each number to the right of the decimal point =
as the numerator, and simplify. For example, looking at the number 0.1234, =
the number 4 is in the fourth decimal place, which constitutes 10<sup>4</su=
p>, or 10,000. This would make the fraction <span class=3D"frac"><span clas=
s=3D"fracnum">1234</span><span class=3D"fracden">10000</span></span>, which=
 simplifies to <span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">617</span><span=
 class=3D"fracden">5000</span></span>, since the greatest common factor bet=
ween the numerator and denominator is 2.</p>

<p>Similarly, fractions with denominators that are powers of 10 (or can be =
converted to powers of 10) can be translated to decimal form using the same=
 principles. Take the fraction <span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum"=
>1</span><span class=3D"fracden">2</span></span> for example. To convert th=
is fraction into a decimal, first convert it into the fraction of <span cla=
ss=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">5</span><span class=3D"fracden">10</spa=
n></span>. Knowing that the first decimal place represents 10<sup>-1</sup>,=
 <span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">5</span><span class=3D"fracde=
n">10</span></span> can be converted to 0.5. If the fraction were instead <=
span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"fracnum">5</span><span class=3D"fracden"=
>100</span></span>, the decimal would then be 0.05, and so on. Beyond this,=
 converting fractions into decimals requires the operation of long division=
.</p>


</div>
